Clearly not. The creature simply whistled and attempted to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite its size, it was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she nearly lost grip on its too smooth scales.
"HOW DO WE KILL THEM ?", shouted Nyssi.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEADS !"
"THIS WON'T BE EASY !"
Thassalin blew, then circled around to get closer to the mountain he called his home. The black beast followed, somewhat panicked when a bolt of fire struck her from behind. The creature hadn't noticed she was no longer alone. Its panic grew when Thassalin slowed down, then hit her hard on the head with his tail, knocking her off her course.
Grognant et sifflant, la créature prit de l'altitude et cracha dans les airs. Tout à coup, tout devint noir, comme si le monstre était en train d'aspirer la lumière du ciel et de remplacer par un nuage de nuit perpétuelle.
N'ayant plus aucune visibilité, Thassalin tenta de battre en retraite, mais rasa la cime des arbres avant de s'écraser dans la clairière. Comme si elle avait su exactement où il était tombé, la créature fonça droit sur lui, entraînant le nuage sombre dans son sillage.
"Kayel !", s'exclama Tenuk alors qu'il s'extirpait du nuage et commençait à voler en cercles pour essayer de repérer Nyssi et Thassalin en dessous, dans l'obscurité. "Que fait-on, Kayel ? Kayel... ? Kayel, où es-tu ?"
En bas, Nyssi se releva tant bien que mal. Elle était sûre de s'être cassé quelque chose, mais ses étranges pouvoirs de guérison tout sauf naturels avaient déjà commencé à faire effet. On ne pouvait pas en dire autant de Thassalin, qui était étendu sur une motte, appuyé contre le seul arbre qui n'avait pas plié sous son poids. Nyssi fit de son mieux pour essayer de rejoindre Thassalin, mais elle ne voyait pas à deux mètres devant elle. Tout était plongé dans le noir, englouti dans les ombres impies. Et dans ces ombres, quelque chose hurlait.
Une horrible queue en forme de gourdin vient s'abattre à côté de Nyssi, la faisant tomber à la renverse. Elle nota toutefois que la queue s'agitait, sans la viser. La créature, du peu que Nyssi pouvait voir et entendre, grognait et griffait les ombres qu'elle avait engendrées. Quelque chose se téléportait à travers l'obscurité, frappant le monstre, le désorientant.
A sudden gunshot echoed, and the monster collapsed silently, lifeless. The darkness surrounding them faded, revealing what had happened. Standing on the creature was Kayel, holding his gun and catching his breath.
"This... is the strangest shadow jump I've ever done... Thanto kat'olon...", panted Kayel. His eyes glowed with a black light, and a dark energy coursed through his body. However, as he spoke, the organic plating of Kayel regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel had strange shadow powers. He used them rarely, as most people considered them impious and rather frightening. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed quite surprised himself.
"Are you okay?" Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yes, I'm fine. I killed something. It'll be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk made his way to land next to him, reverting to his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature was no longer moving, they could better see what it was. Its skin was black as coal and slimy, but the saliva continued to stick to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what this thing was, something screamed and darted out from a nearby bush. However, the beast had no time to reach them, as a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, flinging it to Nyssi's feet. Taking no chances, she grabbed her rifle and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature on the spot.
"Oops...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before awkwardly turning off the engine and jumping out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you all okay?"
"You practically missed the entire action," regretted Tenuk. "Where were you?"
"You all abandoned me. I came here as fast as I could," sighed Retvik. "Can someone tell me what these vile creatures are?"
Retvik's question fortunately received an answer from Thassalin, who had just gotten up. He was all cut and scratched everywhere and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't look too injured.
"YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the horrible corrupt god that we have... helped kill?", stammered Tenuk.
"YES. COMPLETELY. THERE MAY BE OTHERS, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO AIM FOR THEIR HEADS. I'M LACKING A RIFLE. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE, THAT'S NOT FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin walked towards Kayel and patted his head. "THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT LESS KILLING AND LESS ABLE TO DESTROY UNIVERSES."
"Uh... thank you... I guess", said Kayel with a shrug. "So, are we done here?"
Nyssi shrugged, then grabbed her camera to photograph the creatures, now definitely dead. She then took out her favorite dagger, the god of death's dagger, and began cutting off one of the creature's horns, then moving on to the other. But as she finished, the creatures burst into flames and quickly turned into piles of ash. The same thing happened to the horns Nyssi had cut off.
"Well... it's both convenient and very inconvenient," she sighed. "At least I still have the photos..."
